1.1. At least 1 workshop conducted for potential borrowers of the Russian-Kyrgyz Development Fund preferably with no less 30% of women borrowers;

1.2. At least 2 gender responsive and gender-sensitive pre-feasibility studies, business plans, assessments are developed under the technical assistance to potential borrowers of the Russian-Kyrgyz Development Fund ;

1.3.At least 50% of all projects supported the under Activity 1 are received loan from Russian-Kyrgyz Development Fund ;

2.1. At least 1 gender-sensitive prefeasibility studies, business plans, assessments are developed under the technical assistance to potential borrowers of the Eurasian Development Bank.

1.1.   During the COVID-19 pandemic, the Russian-Kyrgyz Development Fund took measures to support the economy in order to minimize the impact of the crisis on the business. As part of these measures, the Russian-Kyrgyz Development Fund has developed new loan products based on the cluster approach in the following areas: development of dairy production; development of meat processing; development of aquaculture. As part of the promotion of the Russian-Kyrgyz Development Funds loan product for the cluster development of dairy production, the project initiated the educational program for the dairy farming entities to gain knowledge on key aspects of dairy farming activities, as well as receive information on the development opportunities of their farms through the financing of the Russian-Kyrgyz Development Fund. 52 farmers have been trained.

1.2.   21 new business project applications had been submitted for technical assistance to develop the feasibility studies for these projects in 2021. out of these 21 applications, 11 projects (the requested funding amount is around 17mln USD) have been approved to receive the support. The development of feasability studies for 2 projects have been completed and submitted to the the Russian-Kyrgyz Development Fund. The development of feasibility studies for other 9 projects is ongoing and the developed feasibility studies of the projects are expected to be submitted to the the Russian-Kyrgyz Development Fund in December 2021.

1.3.   7 projects with developed feasibility studies have been submitted to the Russian-Kyrgyz Development Fund in 2020 and 4 projects have been submitted in 2021. Total = 11 projects. The status of these 11 projects as of the end of November 2021 are as follows: 
a)	The financing is approved (Credit Committee level 1): 2 projects (production of water meters and agriculture). The approved loan amount – 695,000 USD;
b)	The project concept is approved (Credit Committee level 1): 3 projects (the total requested funding amount is 1,002,000 USD). The final credit committee is planned in December 2021;
c)	Rejection by the Russian-Kyrgyz Development Fund: 1 project with a total requested funding amount of 4mln. USD;
d)	Withdrawal by the applicants: 3 projects: the first project with a total requested funding amount of 101 000 USD could not provide the personal guarantor per the requirement of the Russian-Kyrgyz Development Fund; the second project could not implement the the recommendation related to the legal status of the company; thus, the Russian-Kyrgyz Development Fund couldn’t process the application of these 2 projects further without these requirement being met. The concept of the third project has been approved by the Russian-Kyrgyz Development Fund, but the project owner decided to withdraw its application due to the impact of COVID19 on its business (tourism sector);
e) In the process of the review bt the Russian-Kyrgyz Development Fund: 2 projects are currently being reviewed by the Russian-Kyrgyz Development Fund.

2.1.  No feasabiilty study under component 2 have been developed. The EDB informed that they identified 2 potential projects from Tajikistan and Armenia, but no applications have been submitted for these 2 projects. The UNDP COs in Armenia, Tajikistan, Kazahstan and Belarus also didnt have any commercial projects to be considered for this activity.

